<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-662-128  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 662 128.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics  July 1990 v63 n7 p31(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A squeeze on Apple. (Windows 3.0 graphical user interface providescompetition for the Apple Macintosh)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Curran, Lawrence.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Microsoft's introduction of its $149 Windows 3.0 could threatenthe Apple Macintosh market by bringing a graphical user interfaceto less expensive MS-DOS microcomputers.andP;  The icon-driven softwarepackage is expected to extend the life of approximately 27 million80286- and 80386-based microcomputers and workstations by makingan upgrade to a multitasking system easy and economical.andP;  Windows3.0's new memory management capability will allow applications torun faster than under previous versions and also allows DOS-basedmachines to overcome the 640K-byte limit.andP;  Windows 3.0 can run allof the more than 700 applications programs that ran under previousWindows versions and supports several standard interfaces topopular network device drivers.andP;  Microsoft also offers a $225package of Windows 3.0 and a 400 Series Microsoft Mouse.andP;  Anupgrade from previous versions of Windows costs $50.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (product introduction)Apple Computer Inc. (products).andO;Ticker:    AAPL; MSFT.andO;Product:   Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (marketing)Microsoft Windows 3.0 (Graphical user interface) (productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Graphical User InterfaceProduct IntroductionCompetition.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>